Because the European Union will not allow products that have been tested in ways it outlaws, a U.S. firm can keep selling in Europe only if it follows the European rules, not U.S. rules. In practice that means the firm must:

• abandon or sharply limit the animal-testing procedures that the EU forbids;  
• repeat or replace any disallowed tests with methods the EU accepts;  
• document compliance for European regulators.

If it refuses, its goods are barred from the EU market. Thus the stricter European regulations raise compliance costs and often force U.S. companies to change their R-&D and safety-testing practices worldwide so they can continue to export to, or operate in, Europe.
